# Microsoft Entra ID End-To-End Guide

This guide shows how to use Microsoft Entra ID as an OIDC provider for quacklake, how Entra groups and scopes become quacklake principals, how catalog mappings select a DuckLake catalog, how catalog policies create permission profiles, and how end users query data published through the DuckLake catalog.

The examples use one catalog named `finance`, one Entra tenant, one Entra app registration that represents the quacklake API, and Entra access tokens. quacklake verifies the token, maps token claims into an `AuthPrincipal`, resolves the token to exactly one catalog, and evaluates the catalog policy before executing catalog SQL through the Quack catalog.

## What Gets Enforced

There are three separate layers:

| Layer | Configured in | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Provider trust | `/admin/oidc/providers` | Verifies Entra token issuer, audience, algorithm, signature, and expiry. |
| Catalog mapping | `/admin/catalogs/:catalogId/auth-mapping` | Decides whether a verified Entra principal may select this quacklake catalog. |
| Catalog policy | `/admin/catalogs/:catalogId/auth-policy` | Decides which SQL actions and resources that principal may use inside the selected catalog. |

Entra ID does not directly grant table access. It emits identity facts such as `oid`, `tid`, `scp`, `groups`, and `roles`. quacklake maps those facts into one normalized principal and evaluates server-side catalog policy rules.

Important limits for v1:

- Each catalog has one active policy document. Multiple permission profiles are multiple rules in that one document.
- Catalog mapping must resolve an OIDC token to exactly one catalog. Zero matches or matches across multiple catalogs deny authentication.
- Entra `groups` claims usually contain group object IDs, not display names.
- If a user is in too many groups, Entra can emit group overage claims instead of the full `groups` array. quacklake v1 does not call Microsoft Graph to expand group overage claims.
- Column policies are enforced at quacklake's SQL authorization layer.
- `rowPredicate` is currently a catalog-side authorization guard that requires referenced claims to be present. It is not a complete data-file gateway or storage-level row filter.
- DuckDB still needs object-storage credentials to read DuckLake data files. Scope those R2/S3 credentials separately because broad storage credentials can bypass catalog decisions.

## Token Choice

Use Entra access tokens for this guide.

For a quacklake API app registration, end-user clients request an access token for an exposed API scope such as:

```text
api://<quacklake-api-app-id>/Catalog.Access
```

With v2 Entra access tokens, the `aud` claim is the client ID of the API app registration. Configure the quacklake provider `audiences` to that API app ID unless your tenant intentionally issues a different audience.

Do not use an ID token for the normal DuckDB/Quack path unless you deliberately configure quacklake to trust the client application's ID-token audience. ID tokens identify sign-in to the client app; access tokens identify calls to the quacklake API.

## Example Permission Profiles

This guide uses Entra security groups as permission profiles:

| Entra group display name | quacklake profile | Intended access |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `dq-finance-readers` | Reader | Read a safe column set from published finance tables. No writes. |
| `dq-finance-analysts` | Analyst | Read a broader column set, including analytics fields. No writes. |
| `dq-finance-tenant-users` | Tenant user | Read tenant-scoped columns when `tid` is present and rows store Entra tenant IDs. |
| `dq-finance-writers` | Writer | Read and mutate rows in finance tables. No schema drops. |
| `dq-finance-admins` | Catalog admin | Manage schemas, tables, columns, and DuckLake metadata maintenance. |

The actual policy examples use group object IDs:

```text
READERS_GROUP_ID=<object-id-of-dq-finance-readers>
ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID=<object-id-of-dq-finance-analysts>
TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID=<object-id-of-dq-finance-tenant-users>
WRITERS_GROUP_ID=<object-id-of-dq-finance-writers>
ADMINS_GROUP_ID=<object-id-of-dq-finance-admins>
```

Entra group display names are operational labels. quacklake matches the `groups` claim values exactly, so use object IDs when Entra emits object IDs.

## Prerequisites

You need:

- A deployed quacklake Worker.
- Worker secrets set for `ADMIN_TOKEN`, `QUACKLAKE_JWT_SECRET`, and `CONNECTION_SIGNING_SECRET`.
- Azure CLI authenticated to the target tenant.
- Permission in Entra ID to create app registrations, create groups, assign users to groups, and configure token claims.
- DuckDB with DuckLake and Quack extension support.
- R2 or S3 credentials for the DuckLake data path, scoped to the published bucket and prefix.

Set common shell variables:

```sh
export WORKER_URL="https://<worker-host>"
export ADMIN_TOKEN="<quacklake-admin-token>"
export CATALOG_ID="finance"
export TENANT_ID="$(az account show --query tenantId -o tsv)"
```

## 1. Create The quacklake Catalog

Create the catalog and a first-party admin credential for bootstrap:

```sh
scripts/create-jwt.sh \
  --worker-url "$WORKER_URL" \
  --admin-token "$ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  --catalog-id "$CATALOG_ID" \
  --output-file /tmp/quacklake-finance-admin.json
```

The generated first-party JWT is only needed for catalog bootstrap and maintenance. Entra end users will use Entra-issued access tokens.

## 2. Register The quacklake API In Entra ID

Create an app registration that represents the quacklake API:

```sh
API_APP_ID="$(
  az ad app create \
    --display-name quacklake-finance-api \
    --sign-in-audience AzureADMyOrg \
    --query appId \
    -o tsv
)"

API_APP_OBJECT_ID="$(
  az ad app show \
    --id "$API_APP_ID" \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"

API_APP_URI="api://$API_APP_ID"
```

Set the Application ID URI and ask Entra to include security group claims in tokens issued to this API:

```sh
az ad app update \
  --id "$API_APP_ID" \
  --identifier-uris "$API_APP_URI" \
  --set groupMembershipClaims=SecurityGroup
```

Expose a delegated API scope named `Catalog.Access`.

The portal path is:

1. Microsoft Entra admin center.
2. App registrations.
3. `quacklake-finance-api`.
4. Expose an API.
5. Add a scope named `Catalog.Access`.
6. Allow admins and users, or admins only, depending on your tenant policy.

For production, use your normal infrastructure-as-code flow for app registrations and scopes. The essential quacklake values are:

```sh
echo "Tenant issuer: https://login.microsoftonline.com/$TENANT_ID/v2.0"
echo "JWKS URI: https://login.microsoftonline.com/$TENANT_ID/discovery/v2.0/keys"
echo "Audience: $API_APP_ID"
echo "Scope: Catalog.Access"
```

## 3. Create Entra Groups

Create security groups for the permission profiles:

```sh
READERS_GROUP_ID="$(
  az ad group create \
    --display-name dq-finance-readers \
    --mail-nickname dq-finance-readers \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"

ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID="$(
  az ad group create \
    --display-name dq-finance-analysts \
    --mail-nickname dq-finance-analysts \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"

TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID="$(
  az ad group create \
    --display-name dq-finance-tenant-users \
    --mail-nickname dq-finance-tenant-users \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"

WRITERS_GROUP_ID="$(
  az ad group create \
    --display-name dq-finance-writers \
    --mail-nickname dq-finance-writers \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"

ADMINS_GROUP_ID="$(
  az ad group create \
    --display-name dq-finance-admins \
    --mail-nickname dq-finance-admins \
    --query id \
    -o tsv
)"
```

If the groups already exist, read their object IDs instead:

```sh
READERS_GROUP_ID="$(az ad group show --group dq-finance-readers --query id -o tsv)"
ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID="$(az ad group show --group dq-finance-analysts --query id -o tsv)"
TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID="$(az ad group show --group dq-finance-tenant-users --query id -o tsv)"
WRITERS_GROUP_ID="$(az ad group show --group dq-finance-writers --query id -o tsv)"
ADMINS_GROUP_ID="$(az ad group show --group dq-finance-admins --query id -o tsv)"
```

## 4. Assign Users To Profiles

Find a user's Entra object ID:

```sh
READER_USER_ID="$(az ad user show --id reader@example.com --query id -o tsv)"
TENANT_USER_ID="$(az ad user show --id tenant-a@example.com --query id -o tsv)"
ADMIN_USER_ID="$(az ad user show --id admin@example.com --query id -o tsv)"
```

Assign users to groups:

```sh
az ad group member add \
  --group "$READERS_GROUP_ID" \
  --member-id "$READER_USER_ID"

az ad group member add \
  --group "$TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID" \
  --member-id "$TENANT_USER_ID"

az ad group member add \
  --group "$ADMINS_GROUP_ID" \
  --member-id "$ADMIN_USER_ID"
```

Group changes are reflected only in newly-issued tokens. Ask users to sign in again or refresh their token after changing membership.

## 5. Register Entra ID With quacklake

Create the provider document:

```sh
cat >/tmp/entra-finance-provider.json <<JSON
{
  "providerId": "entra-finance",
  "issuer": "https://login.microsoftonline.com/$TENANT_ID/v2.0",
  "jwksUri": "https://login.microsoftonline.com/$TENANT_ID/discovery/v2.0/keys",
  "audiences": ["$API_APP_ID"],
  "algorithms": ["RS256"],
  "clockToleranceSeconds": 60,
  "claimMapping": {
    "subject": "oid",
    "scopes": "scp",
    "groups": "groups",
    "roles": "roles",
    "tenantId": "tid"
  }
}
JSON
```

Install it:

```sh
curl -s -X POST "$WORKER_URL/admin/oidc/providers" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d @/tmp/entra-finance-provider.json
```

For updates, use:

```sh
curl -s -X PUT "$WORKER_URL/admin/oidc/providers/entra-finance" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d @/tmp/entra-finance-provider.json
```

After token verification, quacklake normalizes a matching Entra token into a principal like:

```json
{
  "principal": {
    "issuer": "https://login.microsoftonline.com/<tenant-id>/v2.0",
    "subject": "<user-object-id>",
    "audience": ["<api-app-id>"],
    "scopes": ["Catalog.Access"],
    "groups": ["<group-object-id>"],
    "roles": [],
    "claims": {
      "tenantId": "<tenant-id>"
    },
    "providerId": "entra-finance",
    "authMode": "oidc_jwt"
  }
}
```

## 6. Replace The Catalog Mapping

Catalog mapping answers only one question: can this verified Entra principal select the `finance` catalog?

Require both:

- An access token issued for the quacklake API scope.
- Membership in at least one finance profile group.

```sh
cat >/tmp/finance-entra-auth-mapping.json <<JSON
{
  "mappings": [
    {
      "mappingId": "entra-finance-profiles",
      "providerId": "entra-finance",
      "priority": 100,
      "match": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": [
          "$READERS_GROUP_ID",
          "$ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID",
          "$TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID",
          "$WRITERS_GROUP_ID",
          "$ADMINS_GROUP_ID"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
JSON
```

Install it:

```sh
curl -s -X PUT "$WORKER_URL/admin/catalogs/$CATALOG_ID/auth-mapping" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d @/tmp/finance-entra-auth-mapping.json
```

Why this matters:

- If the token has no `Catalog.Access` scope, it does not select this catalog.
- If the token has none of the configured group IDs, it does not select this catalog.
- If the same token maps to another catalog too, authentication is denied as ambiguous.
- `priority` is metadata in v1. It does not break ties.
- This mapping does not grant read or write access. It only routes the token to the catalog.

For tenant-specific catalogs, make mapping rules mutually exclusive by group or tenant claim:

```json
{
  "mappingId": "entra-tenant-a-finance",
  "providerId": "entra-finance",
  "match": {
    "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
    "groupsAny": ["<tenant-a-finance-group-object-id>"],
    "claims": {
      "tenantId": "<entra-tenant-guid>"
    }
  }
}
```

Use that pattern only when each tenant has a separate quacklake catalog. For one shared catalog, keep catalog mapping broad and enforce profile restrictions in the catalog policy.

## 7. Install Permission Profiles

Write a policy document with multiple profile rules:

```sh
cat >/tmp/finance-entra-auth-policy.json <<JSON
{
  "version": 1,
  "defaultEffect": "deny",
  "rules": [
    {
      "ruleId": "entra-finance-readers-safe-columns",
      "effect": "allow",
      "principal": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": ["$READERS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": ["schema.read", "table.read", "column.read"],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "finance",
        "table": "*",
        "columns": ["id", "tenant_id", "amount", "created_at"]
      }
    },
    {
      "ruleId": "entra-finance-analysts-expanded-columns",
      "effect": "allow",
      "principal": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": ["$ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": ["schema.read", "table.read", "column.read"],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "finance",
        "table": "*",
        "columns": ["id", "tenant_id", "customer_id", "amount", "status", "created_at", "updated_at"]
      }
    },
    {
      "ruleId": "entra-finance-tenant-users",
      "effect": "allow",
      "principal": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": ["$TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": ["schema.read", "table.read", "column.read"],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "finance",
        "table": "invoices",
        "columns": ["id", "tenant_id", "amount", "status", "created_at"]
      },
      "rowPredicate": "tenant_id = \${claims.tenantId}"
    },
    {
      "ruleId": "entra-finance-writers-table-crud",
      "effect": "allow",
      "principal": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": ["$WRITERS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": [
        "schema.read",
        "table.read",
        "table.insert",
        "table.update",
        "table.delete",
        "column.read"
      ],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "finance",
        "table": "*",
        "column": "*"
      }
    },
    {
      "ruleId": "entra-finance-admins-catalog-admin",
      "effect": "allow",
      "principal": {
        "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
        "groupsAny": ["$ADMINS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": [
        "schema.read",
        "schema.create",
        "schema.drop",
        "table.read",
        "table.create",
        "table.insert",
        "table.update",
        "table.delete",
        "table.drop",
        "column.read",
        "column.alter",
        "catalog.admin"
      ],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "*",
        "table": "*",
        "column": "*"
      }
    },
    {
      "ruleId": "deny-entra-reader-secret-columns",
      "effect": "deny",
      "principal": {
        "groupsAny": ["$READERS_GROUP_ID", "$ANALYSTS_GROUP_ID", "$TENANT_USERS_GROUP_ID"]
      },
      "actions": ["column.read"],
      "resource": {
        "schema": "finance",
        "table": "employees",
        "columns": ["salary", "ssn"]
      }
    }
  ]
}
JSON
```

Install it:

```sh
curl -s -X PUT "$WORKER_URL/admin/catalogs/$CATALOG_ID/auth-policy" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d @/tmp/finance-entra-auth-policy.json
```

How evaluation works:

- `defaultEffect: "deny"` denies anything that no allow rule covers.
- Deny rules override allow rules.
- A rule must match principal, action, and resource.
- `scopesAny: ["Catalog.Access"]` requires the Entra access token to include the delegated API scope.
- `groupsAny` matches any Entra group object ID in `principal.groups`.
- `groupsAll` can require a user to be in multiple groups.
- `claims` can require exact normalized claim values, for example `{ "tenantId": "<tenant-guid>" }`.
- `columns` allows only listed projected columns. `SELECT *` requires `column.read` on `*`, so it is denied unless the rule grants `column: "*"` or `columns: ["*"]`.
- `rowPredicate` only matches when referenced claims are present. In this example, `tenantId` maps to Entra `tid`, so table rows must store that Entra tenant GUID for the predicate to be meaningful.
- For hard row isolation in v1, combine catalog policy with tenant-specific data layout, scoped storage credentials, separate catalogs, or published views/materialized subsets.

## 8. Validate With Explain

Get an Entra access token. For a local smoke test, Azure CLI can request a token for the exposed scope when tenant consent and client permissions allow it:

```sh
ENTRA_TOKEN="$(
  az account get-access-token \
    --tenant "$TENANT_ID" \
    --scope "$API_APP_URI/Catalog.Access" \
    --query accessToken \
    -o tsv
)"
```

If Azure CLI is not authorized to request that scope in your tenant, use your normal application sign-in flow to acquire an access token for:

```text
api://<quacklake-api-app-id>/Catalog.Access
```

Ask quacklake to explain the decision:

```sh
curl -s -X POST "$WORKER_URL/admin/authz/explain" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d "{
    \"authString\": \"$ENTRA_TOKEN\",
    \"catalogId\": \"$CATALOG_ID\",
    \"sql\": \"SELECT id, tenant_id, amount, created_at FROM finance.invoices LIMIT 10\"
  }"
```

Expected success indicators:

- `principal.authMode` is `oidc_jwt`.
- `principal.providerId` is `entra-finance`.
- `principal.scopes` contains `Catalog.Access`.
- `principal.groups` contains the expected group object ID.
- `catalog.catalogId` is `finance`.
- `decision.allowed` is `true`.
- `matchedRules` includes a rule such as `entra-finance-readers-safe-columns`.

Try a denied query:

```sh
curl -s -X POST "$WORKER_URL/admin/authz/explain" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d "{
    \"authString\": \"$ENTRA_TOKEN\",
    \"catalogId\": \"$CATALOG_ID\",
    \"sql\": \"SELECT * FROM finance.invoices\"
  }"
```

A reader is expected to be denied because `SELECT *` requires wildcard column access.

## 9. End User DuckDB Setup

End users need two secrets:

- A Quack secret with their Entra access token.
- A storage secret for DuckLake data files.

Create the Quack secret:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE SECRET quacklake_finance (
  TYPE quack,
  TOKEN '<entra-access-token>',
  SCOPE 'quack:<worker-host>:443'
);
```

Create a scoped R2 storage secret. Use credentials that are limited to the bucket and prefix that this user should be able to read or write:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE SECRET finance_lake_r2 (
  TYPE r2,
  KEY_ID '<r2-access-key-id>',
  SECRET '<r2-secret-access-key>',
  ACCOUNT_ID '<cloudflare-account-id>',
  SCOPE 'r2://<bucket>/<prefix>/'
);
```

If your DuckDB build uses the generic S3 secret path for R2:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE SECRET finance_lake_s3 (
  TYPE s3,
  PROVIDER config,
  KEY_ID '<r2-access-key-id>',
  SECRET '<r2-secret-access-key>',
  ENDPOINT '<account-id>.r2.cloudflarestorage.com',
  URL_STYLE 'path',
  REGION 'auto',
  SCOPE 'r2://<bucket>/<prefix>/'
);
```

Attach the DuckLake catalog through Quack:

```sql
ATTACH 'ducklake:quack:<worker-host>:443' AS finance_lake (
  DATA_PATH 'r2://<bucket>/<prefix>/'
);
```

Reader query:

```sql
SELECT id, tenant_id, amount, created_at
FROM finance_lake.finance.invoices
LIMIT 10;
```

Analyst query:

```sql
SELECT tenant_id, status, sum(amount) AS total_amount
FROM finance_lake.finance.invoices
GROUP BY tenant_id, status
ORDER BY total_amount DESC;
```

Writer query:

```sql
INSERT INTO finance_lake.finance.adjustments (id, tenant_id, amount, created_at)
VALUES (1001, '<tenant-guid>', 42.50, now());
```

Queries that exceed the user's profile fail before execution against the catalog. Examples:

- Reader tries `SELECT * FROM finance_lake.finance.invoices`.
- Reader tries `INSERT INTO finance_lake.finance.invoices ...`.
- Analyst tries to read `finance.employees.salary`.
- Tenant user lacks a useful tenant claim or the data does not store the expected tenant GUID.

## 10. How Entra Groups Become Query Permissions

The full path is:

1. User signs in to Entra ID.
2. The client obtains an access token for the quacklake API scope.
3. The access token contains `iss`, `aud`, `oid`, `tid`, `scp`, expiry claims, and group membership in `groups` if group claims are configured and not over the token limit.
4. DuckDB sends the token as the Quack auth string.
5. quacklake verifies the token against the registered provider:
   - `iss` equals the configured tenant issuer.
   - `aud` equals the configured API app ID.
   - `alg` is `RS256`.
   - `kid` resolves in the Entra JWKS.
   - `exp` and `nbf` are valid within clock tolerance.
6. quacklake applies `claimMapping`:
   - `oid` becomes `principal.subject`.
   - `scp` becomes `principal.scopes`.
   - `groups` becomes `principal.groups`.
   - `roles` becomes `principal.roles`.
   - `tid` becomes `principal.claims.tenantId`.
7. quacklake scans catalog auth mappings for this provider.
8. Exactly one catalog mapping must match.
9. The catalog Durable Object stores the principal in the session.
10. Every prepared SQL statement is classified into required actions and resources.
11. The catalog policy decides allow or deny before execution.

## 11. App Roles Alternative

For large tenants, app roles are often a better profile mechanism than raw group claims because they avoid group overage. Assign Entra groups to app roles such as:

- `Finance.Reader`
- `Finance.Analyst`
- `Finance.Writer`
- `Finance.Admin`

Entra emits assigned app roles in the `roles` claim. quacklake maps that claim to `principal.roles`.

Policy rules can then match roles instead of group object IDs:

```json
{
  "ruleId": "entra-role-finance-readers",
  "effect": "allow",
  "principal": {
    "scopesAny": ["Catalog.Access"],
    "rolesAny": ["Finance.Reader"]
  },
  "actions": ["schema.read", "table.read", "column.read"],
  "resource": {
    "schema": "finance",
    "table": "*",
    "columns": ["id", "tenant_id", "amount", "created_at"]
  }
}
```

Use either groups or app roles consistently for a catalog. Mixing both can be useful during migration, but it also makes explain output and audits harder to reason about.

## 12. Operational Patterns

Use groups for stable profiles when group counts are modest:

- `dq-finance-readers`
- `dq-finance-analysts`
- `dq-finance-writers`
- `dq-finance-admins`

Use app roles when:

- Users are members of many groups.
- You want readable role names in tokens.
- You want to assign multiple groups to one quacklake permission profile without listing every group object ID in policy.

Use claims for tenant or organization facts:

- `tid` mapped to `claims.tenantId` when rows store Entra tenant IDs.
- A custom optional claim mapped to `claims.tenantId` when rows store an application tenant identifier.

Use one catalog policy per catalog:

- Add profile rules to the same policy document.
- Keep generated rule ids stable so updates can replace a known profile rule.
- Use deny rules for high-risk columns.
- Keep `defaultEffect: "deny"` outside local bootstrap workflows.

Use `POST /admin/authz/explain` before handing a profile to users:

- Test a known allowed read.
- Test a known denied column.
- Test `SELECT *` when the profile should be column-limited.
- Test a mutation when the profile should be read-only.
- Test tenant users with expected tenant claims.

## 13. Troubleshooting

| Symptom | Likely cause | Fix |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `Invalid auth JWT` | Wrong issuer, audience, signing key, algorithm, expiry, or JWKS. | Check provider config and decode token headers/claims. |
| Token verifies but no catalog resolves | Catalog auth mapping does not match token scopes, groups, roles, or claims. | Inspect `principal` with `/admin/authz/explain`; update mapping. |
| Authentication denied as ambiguous | The same Entra token matches mappings on more than one catalog. | Make mappings mutually exclusive by group, role, claim, or scope. |
| `principal.groups` is empty | Group claims are not configured, or Entra emitted group overage instead of group IDs. | Configure group claims for access tokens, reduce groups, or use app roles. |
| Query denied for `column.read` | Policy does not grant the projected column, or the query uses `SELECT *`. | Select explicit allowed columns or update policy. |
| Tenant rule does not match | The mapped tenant claim does not exist or rows store a different tenant identifier. | Verify `claims.tenantId` in explain and align the row predicate with your data model. |
| Group change not reflected | User is still using an old token. | Sign in again or refresh the token. |
| DuckDB can still read files directly | Storage credentials are broader than the catalog policy. | Issue narrower R2/S3 credentials or separate data prefixes/catalogs. |
| `read_blob()` or DuckLake cleanup fails in Worker | Worker lacks R2 binding for the bucket. | Configure `DUCKLAKE_R2_BINDINGS` and an R2 bucket binding in `wrangler.jsonc`. |

## 14. Security Checklist

- Use access tokens for quacklake API access.
- Configure provider `audiences` to the actual `aud` value in the access token.
- Use group object IDs in policy when Entra emits group object IDs.
- Prefer app roles if users can exceed group claim limits.
- Do not use Entra group membership as the only tenant boundary if users can be in multiple tenant groups. Prefer a tenant claim and mutually exclusive catalog mapping, or separate catalogs.
- Keep the quacklake admin token out of user machines.
- Keep R2/S3 data credentials scoped to the least privilege needed for the user profile.
- Prefer separate storage prefixes or buckets when data-file isolation matters.
- Re-run `/admin/authz/explain` after every policy change.
- Rotate Entra tokens by signing in again after changing group membership, app role assignment, or optional claims.

